post_text: Westfield High School’s weekly student newspaper, Hi's Eye, received a 1st place award by the American Scholastic Press Association. The association critiques college and high school newspapers from around the United States annually and scores them on format, content, presentation, and other criteria. Hi’s Eye was among a number of student newspapers at high schools within a specific enrollment category to receive 1st place recognition for Spring 2020. Congratulations to our student journalists and advisers Shawn McDonald and Gail O'Connor on this prestigious award. Don't forget to subscribe to this award-winning publication here: https://bit.ly/32iXgVO

post_text: The McKinley Elementary PTO Scholarship was presented to Westfield High School seniors Anastasia Fowler and Casimir Malek, in recognition of their outstanding achievements both in the classroom and in our community. This inaugural scholarship was made possible by McKinley School parents, as part of funds raised by the PTO’s annual McKinley Social Fundraiser. The scholarship was awarded to McKinley alum who continue to live the motto of "Grow Our Hearts and Our Minds." Read more here: https://bit.ly/2WINnO1

post_text: From WHS Principal Mary Asfendis regarding today’s Westfield High School Graduation: As the forecast has improved and the chance of storms is significantly less than it was earlier this week, we are proceeding with today’s ceremony. Please arrive no later than 2:30 so that we may line up to begin promptly at 3:00 pm. We will abbreviate parts of the ceremony in case the weather turns and, in the worst-case scenario, if a thunderstorm occurs, we will evacuate the field to Edison and Lincoln Schools.
text: From WHS Principal Mary Asfendis regarding today’s Westfield High School Graduation: As the forecast has improved and the chance of storms is significantly less than it was earlier this week, we are proceeding with today’s ceremony. Please arrive no later than 2:30 so that we may line up to begin promptly at 3:00 pm. We will abbreviate parts of the ceremony in case the weather turns and, in the worst-case scenario, if a thunderstorm occurs, we will evacuate the field to Edison and Lincoln Schools.

post_text: Our "No Place for Hate" committees are working hard to address ways we can support our community. On Wednesday, Westfield High School held a virtual conversation on race, with more than 60 students and staff in attendance. The group broke into smaller sessions to discuss feelings, frustrations, experiences, and ideas before coming back together as a whole to examine race, inequality, and social justice.

post_text: Edison's first Virtual Career Day was attended by more than 150 students, teachers, and community members, who welcomed 12 guests including a biomedical engineer who designs and tests equipment used by doctors, a cybersecurity specialist who served in the U.S. Army, an interior designer who has designed spaces for YouTube, Google, UPS and others, and the founder of the non-profit organization Mission Clean Water which helps to supply water to underprivileged communities. "We believe that providing students with an opportunity to see how people turn their passions into fulfilling careers is a worthwhile endeavor to spark inspiration, especially with remote learning challenging students' abilities to feel connected and excited," say teachers Marc Lazarow and Julia Torsiello who organized the virtual event.
text: Edison's first Virtual Career Day was attended by more than 150 students, teachers, and community members, who welcomed 12 guests including a biomedical engineer who designs and tests equipment used by doctors, a cybersecurity specialist who served in the U.S. Army, an interior designer who has designed spaces for YouTube, Google, UPS and others, and the founder of the non-profit organization Mission Clean Water which helps to supply water to underprivileged communities. "We believe that providing students with an opportunity to see how people turn their passions into fulfilling careers is a worthwhile endeavor to spark inspiration, especially with remote learning challenging students' abilities to feel connected and excited," say teachers Marc Lazarow and Julia Torsiello who organized the virtual event.

post_text: The Westfield High School Marching Blue Devils will hold a virtual interest meeting for all potential new members and parents on Thursday, May 14th, at 7:30 pm. The Marching Band is an ensemble available to all 2020/21 9th through 12th graders who attend WHS or the VoTech. Students receive academic credit, a varsity letter, and are eligible for a gym exemption. There are positions available for instrumentalists, those with piano experience, or those who have a background or an interest in dance. To register to attend the interest meeting, please visit www.westfieldhsbands.org.

post_text: Members of the Westfield Debate Team were among 415 students from 55 schools in 21 states and 2 countries (Canada and Korea) to compete in the Georgetown International Tournament on April 3-5, the first virtual tournament of its kind. Westfield fielded three middle school teams, a novice high school team and a varsity team. Tage Mehta, an 8th grader at Edison Intermediate School was a quarterfinalist in the event. Other student debaters were Edison students Patrick Cadigan, Allison Collins, Carson Donnelly, Yenjay Hu and Dillon Ma, Roosevelt student Altai Abrams and Mira Mehta and Kailey Zhao from Westfield High School (pictured in a pre-COVID-19 photograph). Congratulations to all.

post_text: Parents and students (grades 7-11) at Edison, Roosevelt, Westfield High School are invited to attend an online information session for the Westfield Debate Team on Tuesday, April 28. There will be a mini demonstration debate from 6:30 - 7:00 p.m. followed by an information session at 7:00 p.m. Practice schedules, time commitments and pre-requisites will be reviewed. Both parents and students are strongly encouraged to attend. We will be offering our first pre-team opportunity on Tuesdays & Thursdays from May 7-June 11. Please RSVP for the info session at this link: https://bit.ly/3bBdxaV. You will receive a meeting code. The Westfield Debate Team is a partnership among the Westfield PTC Gifted Education Committee, Westfield Public Schools and the Westfield Area Y. For more information please email westfielddebateteam@gmail.com.

post_text: More examples of our school community helping out in this time of need. The Westfield Education Association (WEA) recently supported both Westfield's first responders and local businesses, with pizza deliveries by Outta Hand and Gennaro's to Westfield police and fire stations, along with the First Aid Squad. Members of the WEA also plan to work with the Rotary Club of Westfield to help communities in need and, through a generous donation from a Westfield resident, recently provided gift cards to families in need of food. "The WEA is committed to being a positive part of the Westfield community," says WEA president Gail Alston.

post_text: Whether donating 10,000 medical gloves to an area hospital, helping to disinfect Westfield police vehicles, or setting up a social media fundraiser to buy grocery gift cards for families in need, the Westfield Public Schools community is pitching in to help during this public health crisis. “There are so many unsung heroes in our school district, including staff members, students and families who put aside their own worries to extend a helping hand to others with greater responsibilities and concerns,” says Superintendent Dr. Margaret Dolan. “Of course, our educators are everyday heroes as they work to provide not only meaningful remote instruction but to also connect with each of their students in a reassuring way during this isolating time.” Read full story here: https://www.westfieldnjk12.org/apps/news/article/1198655

post_text: WHS math teacher Callie Campbell tells a math joke every day in class. "Once we shifted to online learning, my students were still reaching out and asking for the daily joke," says the Westfield native. So she expanded the idea and now posts both a math joke and puzzle in the windows of her Westfield home on a fairly high-trafficked street. "I hope the math joke and puzzle bring a smile or chuckle to people in this time of uncertainty while also serving as a fun learning tool for people of all ages," says Campbell.

The 27th Annual Awareness Expo will be held on Wednesday, March 11 at Edison Intermediate School from 7:15-9:45 p.m. Presented by the Westfield PTC – Special Education Committee, the Awareness Expo will provide parents and educators of special needs children with information and resources to aid in their ongoing education and growth. The event is open to the public and free of charge. A complete agenda of the evening's informative sessions can be found here: https://bit.ly/37G2lqF. Please register to attend at https://tinyurl.com/wewc4np.

post_text: As part of the district’s continuing commitment to Social and Emotional Learning (SEL), McKinley school counselor Mary Beth Herits teamed up with media specialist/librarian Stacey Director to focus on the self-awareness and self-management SEL competencies with students, reading “I am Human” by Susan Verde and leading classes in an activity on recognizing and managing emotions. The students used water bottles, food coloring and glitter glue to illustrate and express differing emotions. More photos here: https://bit.ly/37wDpSy

post_text: More good news from Westfield High School. post_text: As part of the scientific study of pebbles, sand and silt, Washington 2nd graders recently created sand sculptures. "Students mixed sand with a cornstarch matrix to make durable sand sculptures," says teacher Christine Olenick. "They had to determine how much sand and matrix to combine together to produce the best results."
